They have even been reported as having "voluptuous breasts" (Roy Hertz et al., 1966; Valentine, 1969; Polani, 1970). John McLean Morris, the gynecologist who reviewed and summarized all of the existing scientific literature on CAIS women in 1953 (including 82 cases) and gave their condition the (now-obsolete) name "testicular feminization", described their breasts as "unusually large" and "jumbo-sized" (Morris, 1953; Quigley et al., 1995). He additionally said in his famous 1953 review that they had "normal female breasts, often with a tendency to be overdeveloped" (Morris, 1953). In actuality however, some CAIS women have large breasts while some have small breasts (Wisniewski et al., 2000), and we have no clear data that their breasts are in fact larger on average. The variation in breast growth in CAIS women parallels the same large variation in breast size between individuals that's seen in women in general.

Maybe, but it's a gamble. Some people regain all their hair, some regain none. If it's been ten years, though, I think you may be out of luck. I don't think it's common to regain more than a year or two worth of hair loss. HRT may not stop your hair loss at all, just look at the boomer trannies and IT'S MA'AMs who started late in life and probably had pretty high test before, the damage is already done. FtMs who detransition naturally produce E and they don't regain their lost hair either. Definitely a case of you want to start as early as possible.

If hair is all you care about though, you don't need E, and it probably shouldn't be anywhere near the top of the list of options. E inhibits hair loss as a side effect, the actual thing that stops hair loss is low testosterone. Higher E levels will dampen your T, that's how monotherapy works, but E will have other effects, including breasts, which is going to be a problem if you want to present as conventionally masculine. No, it's not as simple as "I'll just bind if they get too big", you'll also get a different weight distribution and skin oils, people will notice, and binding isn't comfortably even with a smaller chest.

it's all conjecture, nobody knows. Cis puberty happens by itself so the specifics aren't important, and nobody cares about trannies enough to do much good conclusive research on the best methods for hrt.
The reason estrone is talked about for breast growth, is because there's some evidence (not hard proof) that oral E is better for early breast growth, and oral gives higher estrone. I think there are also cases where hondosed mtfs get really big breasts on low doses of oral E, but little progress in anything else.
A lot of this comes from dr. powers, who is an advocate for the idea that estrone is important for early breast growth, and that estrone should be the dominant hormone until tanner 3.
But as you can see from that study, there isn't a lot of actual evidence to support it.
I think the best way to go about it is probably just to transition normally as well as you can, and then after a year or two when you're on monotherapy, if your breast growth isn't satisfactory you can always add 1mg oral E or something, which apparently has been effective in other people. But again, just conjecture.

Not trans, but I thought it would make sense to ask here.

Anyone knows a good throughout guide (or a wiki) into various hormones? What's the difference between free test and total test, dht, how does test and various estrogens work together? etc.

Also, can I microdose on HRT to become slightly more feminine? Does HRT kill your muscles?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>28897557
Look at the picture in OP. Also check out https://transfemscience.org/articles/transfem-intro/

The basics is, if you take any estrogen at all, you are going to develop breasts, which doesn't sound like something you're interested in. Heightened levels of estrogen will furthermore suppress your testosterone production, to the extent that a large dose (called estradiol monotherapy) can essentially block it entirely.
You can try taking only an antiandrogen (cypro will probably be the easiest and best option). You won't "feminise", but you will "de-masculinise". It'll kill your libido (it's literally chemical castration) and make erections very rare, but that's reversible if you just stop taking the medication. Over prolonged time it's going to cause brittle bones and other health issues associated with menopause, so bear that in mind and live healthy. Don't try to do this with bica, that one doesn't actually stop test production, just your body's ability to make use of it. All the leftover testosterone turns into estrogen and you'll grow tits.
Testosterone is the stuff that builds muscles, so without it you're going to build muscle at more or less the same rate a woman does, which is significantly slower, but you do keep any muscle you already have, and also your masculine bone structure. Even if you go full MtF HRT you'll be stronger than just about any natural female. If you keep up your exercise you won't lose muscle, but you may lose your appetite (or gain a lot of it), and you will find it difficult to build new muscle.

Needless to say, if you plan to have children, it's best to do that before you start messing with your hormones. And even if you don't want kids, at least go to a sperm bank. If in the future you change your mind, you'll be happy you did. In theory stopping the medication will eventually return your sperm count, but testicular atrophy is a case of better safe than sorry.

Goal of the thread: Go out for a walk, or try to get any other form of small exercise (walking stairs for 5 mins for example)
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

If any resource below is unhelpful, please let me know. I can't assert their quality on my own.

resources:

Exercise, diet, weight loss/gain: >>>/fit/17018018 (sticky)
NIMH brochures on mental health topics (Depression, BPD, ADHD, etc): https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications
ED: https://www.eatingdisorderhope.com/treatment-for-eating-disorders

General advice from Anons: https://0x0.st/o5Og.txt

we currently lack (mental) health resources.
Suggestions and debate for which to include encouraged!

Tell me more, anon. The first thing you need to know is that, as the OP says, relapsing is part of healing. These roadblocks are natural and frequent, especially in the beginning. The problem usually lies in what conclusion you draw from them, because they reinforce the idea of struggling not being worth it. You must view these days as isolated exceptions, and disregard the decisions made that day as hiccups. That isn't easy, but you can do it.
>>28865905
That's a BMI of roughly 21 (good) if I did the math right, and you seem healthy and physically fit. In that case it really is just your self image that is an issue. Self image can be such a bitch to work on, and I can't think of a one size fits all recommendation. But one thing that you need to keep in mind about looks is that perspective and aesthetics are not entirely rational things, and that it is sometimes for the best to recall that you can mold your views as time passes more by habituation than by trying to argue your way out of feeling like that.

>>28882846
your pain is not validated by how deeply you can cut yourself but by your ability to recognize and acknowledge it. the sharp sting of the cut, the physical mark, the bleeding - these all cause you and others to further recognize your pain, but they aren't the only thing that can do this. your pain, your suffering, your agony, even your apathy - these are all already valid emotions without the marks on your arm.

i thought i'd inevitably train myself to cut deeper until i could kill myself doing it - instead, i just wound up with a bunch of vertical scars that make people's eye widen when they notice them on my pale skin. i don't regret anything i've ever done, but i firmly consider cutting myself a mistake. one with valuable lessons, but a mistake.

when i call this shit 'pussy shit,' it's not because it's not deeper - though that does require a certain kind of bravery or stupidity - it's because you're likely realizing it's not productive or helpful and on the verge of getting addicted to feeling that pain, watching the blood flow, making some sort of alteration that you won't be able to step back as proof of what you're going through.

for what it's worth, i believe that you're hurting. i believe that your pain is real. but what would get me to believe it's more real than anything is you admitting to yourself it's real without this. bravery isn't cutting deeper, it's sitting beside your pain and restraining that urge to prove it to yourself on your body. it's looking deep in its eye and letting it know you can see it and that you're going to do something about it.

that promise ring is something beautiful you did for yourself - a commitment you made to see something through and a proof of your resolve. it's brave to follow those hopes and dreams because they'll cause more pain than you could ever put on your arm and bring much more beauty.

>QOTT1: Do you have a specific meal or food item you always eat on Christmas?
My mom always makes a chocolate chess pie, but I also have started making homemade eggnog around this time as well.

>QOTT2: Have any holiday recipes to share with the rest of us? Be it food, drink or anything in between.
Well I'm glad you asked OP
Let me repost the recipe from last thread, since I need to make a few corrections

12 egg yolks
1 cup of sugar
2 cups heavy cream
4 cups whole milk
About a teaspoon nutmeg
A pinch of salt
teaspoon vanilla
teaspoon of cinnamon

Blend the egg yolks and sugar together until smooth and creamy
Heat the cream and milk over medium heat until it gets nearly scalding
Temper the eggs with the cream and milk mixture, then put it back onto the heat
Stir continuously until the mixture is thick enough to coat the back of a wooden spoon
(if you are concerned about raw/undercooked eggs, you can use a thermometer and make sure it reaches 160F/70C)
Add the spices and vanilla, then refrigerate
Serve with freshly ground nutmeg and your choice of rum or whiskey

A note about this recipe: I use a dozen eggs to reach a thicker consistency, and then thin it with a spirit later. If you don't intend to spike the drink, use 8 egg yolks.

posts.name: Seal
posts.com:
And I didn't get to post it cuz of the character limit:

The other recipe I've got on hand is for shortbread cookies, which are generally very simple recipes. This one is intended to be used for jam sandwich cookies, picrel is last year's batch

For the cookies:
3/4 cups of butter, warmed to room temperature
1/2 teaspoon of salt
2 3/4 cups of all purpose flour
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
1/2 cups sugar

Blend the butter until it's fluffy, then blend in sugar and salt
Next, blend the egg and vanilla
Then finally the flour.
Knead the dough into a smooth ball, and divide into equal halves
Roll it out and press it into shapes

For picrel, I used a couple drinking glasses, one large and one small, to make the bottom and top halves.

For the filling: any fruit preserve or jam you like!
For the garnish: a dusting of powdered sugar will do

I'll actually be making these cookies later today, so I can report back and reassure everyone that they're still as tasty as I remember.

not really any in particular, I think. more like I just had specific ideas in mind for things I really wanted to make (starting with a chat bot, and then certain kinds of websites, etc.) and I just sort of implicitly learned as I went, piece-by-piece. I'd just google each thing I wanted to do and read whatever google returned. I never used a book or course or anything, minus like 5 exercises from https://learnpythonthehardway.org/python3/ex1.html to just get the absolute basics

really, the only prerequisite skill is knowing how to assess google results quickly and effectively. this is more important than anything else. so many people don't really know how to use google properly and don't have the intuitive "this is spam/worthless" sense. if you know how to google you should know within milliseconds if something is worth clicking, and then you should know within a second if it's worth staying on

learning how to google = learning how to learn

https://voca (dot)ro/1ezg3zflAg57
Larynx exercises are important, not the end all of voice training but it helps to reduce any bass resonance without using a dumb falsetto.
A really big thing that helped it *click* in my mind is focusing on your resonance and the “shape” of your words; I practiced speaking while pushing the tip my tongue against the back of my bottom teeth while I spoke. This helps produce softer vowels.

Another thing that can only help you (even if it sucks) is recording yourself all the time. Listen back to it all, figure out which parts make you cringe the most and try and change how you say those vowels. Having another voice to mimic is helpful - simple ones like the stereotypical valley girl can help you intentionally learn the importance of feminine cadence as well
